==English==

===Etymology===
From French [[vis-à-vis#French|vis-à-vis]] 'face to face'.

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/vi:zɑːˈvi:/}}

===Preposition===
'''vis-à-vis'''

# In relation to.
# (As) opposed to

====Translations====
*Russian: [[по отношению к]] (po otnošéniju k + [[dative]])

===Noun===
{{en-noun|vis-à-vis}}

# ''(Historical)'' A small horse-drawn [[carriage]] for two people sitting facing each other.
#:*'''1761''': there is not a greater difference between a single-horse chair and madam ''Pompadour''’s '''''vis a vis''''', than betwixt a single amour, and an amour thus nobly doubled — Laurence Sterne, ''The Life & Opinions of Tristram Shandy, Gentleman'', vol. 3 (Penguin 2003, p. 188)

===Adverb===
'''vis-à-vis'''
#''(archaic)'' In a position facing a specified or implied subject.

====Translations====
*Catalan: [[en relació a]]
*Russian: [[друг]] [[против]] [[друг|друга]] (drug prótiv drúga)
*Serbian: [[licem u lice]]
[[Category:English words spelled with diacritics or ligatures|Vis-a-vis]]


